en:
Anne-Charlotte Moulard grew up in a small seaside town on the northern coast of England. After studying art direction
and photography, she assisted the photographer Rankin in London. It was here that she developed her own particular vision, made up of cinematic references, surrealism and narratives. From editorials for magazines to campaigns for major brands, she weaves the contours of this unusual career path, oscillating between commissions and artistic series, not forgetting film direction (Early Bird, 2019 and Thermal, 2022).

In 2022, as part of the Planches Contact festival, she was finally able to take her taste for figures of speech - litote,
syncopation and ellipsis. With L√©on a ras√© C√©sar √† No√´l (Leon shaved Caesar at Christmas), whose title is a palindrome, she takes advantage of her three-month residency to explore the Normandy region in search of meaning. Anne-Charlotte chooses the grain of silver as a means of revealing unresolved feelings and framing timeless images. Dreaming of a sensory narrative, as Andre√Ø Tarkovsky did, she chose to draw the sketches she had dreamt up during her scouting, and to transcribe them into images. Like dreams, her final narrative is fragmented and non-linear, leaving room for interpretation.
Emmanuelle Hutin?s text, which accompanies the exhibition at Le grand bain in Deauville, also borrows its form from surrealist processes
playing on repetition and sound. Finally, the exhibition itself is conceived as a M√∂bius ribbon, a set without beginning or end, echoing the title to reinforce the notion of infinity in this artistic project.

After Deauville, the series returns this summer to Yport, its home port.
